<article>
    <h1>Balestier</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201206/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-06"><time>2020-12-06</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ong Sor Fern</span>
    </section>

    <p>DU­RA­TION AND DIF­FI­CULTY</p>
    <p>Three hours, about 9,000 steps. Note that the Tan Tock Seng side of the walk is a bit hilly. Mod­er­ately easy walk.</p>
    <p>HIGH­LIGHTS</p>
    <p>Sun Yat Sen Nanyang Memo­rial Hall; Maha Sasana Ramsi Burmese Bud­dhist Tem­ple; Shaw Brothers film stu­dio; Loong Fatt Tau Sar Piah; Balestier Mar­ket; for­mer Man­dalay Road Hos­pi­tal; Goh Chor Tua Pek Kong Tem­ple; Art Deco apart­ment blocks; Sim Kwong Ho shop­houses; Loy Kee Best Chicken Rice; Sing Hon Loong Bak­ery (Ghee Leong); Wham­poa Food Mar­ket</p>
    <p>THE GOOD</p>
    <p>This trail is one for the food­ies, as the area is packed with food of­fer­ings along­side the his­tory. In fact, Roots.gov.sg of­fers three mini trails – themed on ar­chi­tec­ture, her­itage and food – for this neigh­bour­hood. There is a fair bit of over­lap, so it is easy to com­bine all three for a com­pre­hen­sive walk that in­cludes much-needed snack breaks.</p>
    <p>Start at Sun Yat Sen Nanyang Memo­rial Hall, which has re­cently re­freshed its gal­leries, for an in­depth look at Dr Sun’s rev­o­lu­tion­ary ties to Sin­ga­pore and South­east Asia. Right next door is the elab­o­rately dec­o­rated Maha Sasana Ramsi Burmese tem­ple.</p>
    <p>The Jalan Am­pas stu­dio, where the leg­endary P. Ram­lee shot many of his clas­sic movies for Shaw Brothers, can be a hit or miss, de­pend­ing on whether the gates are open. The build­ings look rather di­lap­i­dated, but a faded Shaw logo and a gi­ant red sign re­quest­ing “si­lence” hint at more glam­orous days.</p>
    <p>Head over to Balestier Mar­ket, the only sur­viv­ing ru­ral mar­ket built in 1922, for a cold drink and snack. Boon Pisang Goreng serves a lovely ba­nana frit­ter and, more un­usu­ally, a nian gao and yam frit­ter.</p>
    <p>A stop at Goh Chor Tua Pek Kong Tem­ple can be ac­com­pa­nied with an­other snack break, since Com­bat Durian is right be­hind the only sur­viv­ing per­ma­nent wayang stage in Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>Across the road are the Art Deco apart­ments and Sim Kwong Ho shop­houses, in be­tween which are the fa­mous Lam Yeo Cof­fee Pow­der com­pany and Loy Kee Best Chicken Rice, in case you need more sus­te­nance.</p>
    <p>THE BAD</p>
    <p>The old hos­pi­tal build­ings take a bit of an up­hill trek to get to and are worth it only for the most hard­core her­itage devo­tees. The for­mer nurses’ quar­ters at 11 Man­dalay Road are now home to the sleek high-rise of the Lee Kong Chian School of Medicine Novena Cam­pus, while the for­mer Mid­dle­ton Hos­pi­tal (once the Com­mu­ni­ca­ble Dis­eases Cen­tre) is closed to the pub­lic. The for­mer pav­il­ion wards are still there, but are in­ac­ces­si­ble due to con­struc­tion works.</p>

